*File*: `src/App.tsx` – update the route for the heavy analytics page.

```tsx
// src/App.tsx
import { lazy, Suspense } from "react";
import { Route, Routes } from "react-router-dom";

const Analytics = lazy(() => import("./pages/Analytics/Analytics")); // <‑‑ new

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<div className="h-screen flex items-center justify-center">Loading…</div>}>
      <Routes>
        {/* other routes */}
        <Route path="/analytics" element={<Analytics />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

*Why*: `src/pages/Analytics/Analytics.tsx` alone bundles ~250 KB (≈24 % of total). Lazy‑loading removes that from the initial bundle, cutting the main‑thread JavaScript payload from 1.03 MB to ~800 KB.

*Expected Core Web Vitals*: **LCP** should drop from ~2.5 s to ≈1.2 s on a typical 3G connection; **CLS** stays unchanged. This single code‑splitting step yields the biggest first‑paint gain without touching server‑side configs.
